/shrug<br>
<br>
Using Epic as well as 60 water and 59 air in the new Cazic Thule (where a broken mez can be very lethal) for several weeks now, I have yet to see, or to have an Enchanter see, a mez broken by a pet.  Standard tactic is pet tanks adds until the enchanter mezzes them...pet will cease attacking AS SOON as mez lands...which a melee would have a hard time timing right, so Enchanters are loving having the pet take the hits while they lock things down instead of their own fragile bodies.<br>
<br>
I am quite sure the mezzes mentioned in this thread are being broken in some non-pet manner and THEN the pet is no longer barred from attacking the (now unmezzed) mob, and so promptly jumps in to the fray.  This would appear to be the pet breaking the mez.<br>
<br>
It IS possible there is a glitch with procs landing late, but I have yet to see that, despite a thorough review of hundreds of logged and parsed fights.  Not once did a proc message land on a mob after a mez message.  Even when the air pet began casting its stun/dd (with casting time) and a mez landed *during the cast time*, there was never any spell lands messages(resists of stun in CT on tash/malo mobs are rare), which therefore leads me to believe that a pet can IN NO WAY attack/damage a mezzed mob.  The mob is not there as far as pet is concerned....heh, the mob probably gets a &quot;Jobobtik tries to cast a spell on you, but you are protected&quot; message :P<br>
<br>
Until i see some logged proof, and not just &quot;I think my pet broke a mez&quot;, I will assume they do not break mezzes as my research indicates.  My guess is that pets were so often the scapegoats for broken mezzes (guilty or not), that people who aren't informed on these things still point the accusing finger, and once again false information spreads.<br>
<br>
Mistress Finraziel<br>
Archmage<br>
